snippet.textDisplay:
Not sure where the internet responds regarding the turbo rig's power output. My semi-educated guess is as follows:
(Assumes the turbo is amazing)


98 Octane: Running 5.9psi Boost (Dynamic CR of maybe 13:1 with cam timing overlap), AFR 13:1 (rich), Redline @ 6,600RPM = 108.6 Wheel kW or 145.6 Wheel HP


E85: (Requires better fuel pump, injectors and flex fuel sensor) Running 7.4psi Boost (Dynamic CR of 15:1), AFR 9.75:1, Redline @ 6,600 RPM = 156.3 Wheel kW or 209.6 Wheel HP. (Although this will probably destroy the motor)

snippet.textDisplay:
Really quick check to see how garbage the turbo is. If the oil inlet fitting is drilled with a small orifice, its junk. That means their clearances are too bad to avoid starving the engine and leaking oil out the turbo shaft seals. The turbo will run for a while on just a splash of oil with the journal supported hydrodynamically, but it'll burn up.

If there's no orifice, either the manufacturer is perfectly willing to sell turbos that will oil starve and wreck engines, or their turbo is actually well constructed enough that the bearings meter and allow oil pressure to develop, running as they should.
